class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;the</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;keywords</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x003C;span</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">class="cmti-10"&#x003E;fly-fishing</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;Vermont&#x003C;/span&#x003E;.</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;Searching</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;the</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;web</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;is</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;something</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;we</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">do</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;every</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;day</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;with</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;easy</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;but</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;it&amp;#8217;s</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;technically</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;challenging</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;mostly</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;because</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;of</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">the</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;scale</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;of</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;information</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(i.e.,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;webpages)</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;on</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;the</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;web.</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;So</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;how</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;do</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;I</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;get</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">information</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;about</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;fly-fishing</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;in</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;Vermont.</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;I</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;query</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;a</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;search</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;engine</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;(or</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;Google)</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">which</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;is</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;an</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;information</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;retrieval</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;systems</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;and</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;it</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sends</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;me</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;back</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;URLs</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;to</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;sites</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">that</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;have</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;keywords</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;fly-fishing</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;and</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;Vermont</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;embedded</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;in</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;them</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;and</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;the</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;URL</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;are</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;ranked.</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x003C;!--l.</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;55--&#x003E;&#x003C;p</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;class="noindent"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003E;&#x003C;hr</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;class="figure"&#x003E;&#x003C;div</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;class="figure"</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x003E;&#x003C;table</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;class="figure"&#x003E;&#x003C;tr</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;class="figure"&#x003E;&#x003C;td</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;class="figure"</span><br /><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">====</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">SNIP</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">====</span><br /><br /></div></div>
<!--l. 146--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">Tags, URLs and keywords</span>. HTML uses tags to mark-up HTML elements. There are a number of
different tags in use in HTML some more common that others. In the HTML snippet above there are a
number of <span 
class="cmti-10">tags</span>; for example,
<!--l. 148--><p class="noindent" ><span class="obeylines-h"><span class="verb"><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x003C;html</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003E;,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;head&#x003E;,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;title&#x003E;&#x003C;/title&#x003E;,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;/head&#x003E;&#x003C;body,</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;h1</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;class="likepartHead"}</span></span></span><br 
class="newline" />
<!--l. 150--><p class="noindent" >The tutorial goes into tags in details.
<!--l. 152--><p class="noindent" >We are interested collecting URLs from HTML files because we need to go and collect those pages. The
<span 
class="cmti-10">URL tag </span>important to us; that is,
<!--l. 154--><p class="noindent" ><span class="obeylines-h"><span class="verb"><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x003C;a</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;href="http://www.google.com/corporate/history.html"</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003E;</span></span></span>
<!--l. 156--><p class="noindent" >The <span class="obeylines-h"><span class="verb"><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x003C;a&#x003E;</span></span></span> tag defines an anchor. An anchor is used to create a link to another document by using the
href or to create a bookmark inside a document using the name or id attribute. We will only
consider href URLs. Tags usually come in pairs like <span class="obeylines-h"><span class="verb"><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x003C;a&#x003E;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;and</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#x003C;/a&#x003E;</span></span></span> The first tag in a pair is
the start tag and the second tag is the end tag and the text the tags represents the element
content.
<!--l. 158--><p class="noindent" >When looking at a HTML file we are interested in the keywords only. So we want to parse the HTML file
for words; for example, <span 
class="cmti-10">keywords </span>such as,
<!--l. 160--><p class="noindent" ><span class="obeylines-h"><span class="verb"><span 
class="cmtt-10">fly</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;fishing</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;Vermont</span></span></span>.
<!--l. 162--><p class="noindent" >Can you find these keywords in the snippet above (they are near the end). Notice that keywords
are not embedded in tags. In fact, for TinySearch, we define keywords as being outside of
tags.
<!--l. 164--><p class="noindent" >So when TinySearch downloads a webpage of HTML source in needs to parse the page and remove URLs
(because it needs to go crawl them too) and KEYWORDS that users might be interested in running
queries against (such as fly fishing Vermont).
<!--l. 166--><p class="noindent" >Don&#8217;t worry that you don&#8217;t know all the HTML syntax. We plan to provide you with a parser C
function. Feel free not to use our parser and write your own if you like (and if you have time). If
you are interested more information of the curremnt specification check out the <a 
href="http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/about.html" >HTML 4
specification</a>
<!--l. 168--><p class="noindent" >
<h3 class="likesectionHead"><a 
 id="x1-7000"></a>Talking to a webserver using HyperText Transfer Protocol (HTTP)</h3>
<!--l. 170--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-10">HTTP</span>.<a 
href="http://www.w3.org/Protocols/" >HyperText Transfer Protocol (HTTP)</a>is used between your client browser and the
server to transfer plain text HTML files. The URL defines what webpage is transfered, e.g,
http://www.google.com/corporate/history.html HTTP itself is a very simple request/response
protocol that get its reliable transport support from TCP (the famous Transmission Control
                                                                                  
                                                                                  
Protocol).
<!--l. 172--><p class="noindent" >Want to talk to a real-life webserver? They have to be publicly open for business so we can talk plain text
HTTP to them. And, if we are nice and get all the syntax right they will provide us with whatever we
ask for. The basic protocol is that the client sends a request called a <span 
class="cmti-10">GET </span>and the server
responds with a response. Webservers &#8220;listen&#8221; for requests on the well-know port 80. We will talk
more about IP address and ports when we cover socket programming later in the course. But
suffice to say that the Computer Science webserver is listening for requests (e.g., http GET
commands) at IP address 129.170.213.101 (use host www.cs.dartmouth.edu) port 80. So let&#8217;s start a
conversation with the server. We have to first connect to the server and open up a reliable
stream to host www.cs.dartmouth.edu at port 80 . We will use telnet to do this. After that
we will form a GET message and let the server know our hostname. Then see what it will
do.
<div 
class="colorbox" id="colorbox2"><div class="BVerbatimInput"><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">[atc@dhcp-210-161</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;l10]</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;telnet</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;www.cs.dartmouth.edu</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;80</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">Trying</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;129.170.213.101...</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">Connected</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;to</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;katahdin.cs.dartmouth.edu.</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">Escape</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;character</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;is</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;&#8217;^]&#8217;.</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">GET</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;/~campbell/index.html</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;HTTP/1.1</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">host:</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;moose.cs.dartmouth.edu</span><br /><br /><br /></div></div>
<!--l. 191--><p class="noindent" >Make sure you hit carriage return twice after typing in host: moose.cs.dartmouth.edu <br 
class="newline" />newline
<!--l. 193--><p class="noindent" >The nice webserver responds with the webpage http://www.cs.dartmouth.edu/&#x00A0;campbell/index.html<br 
class="newline" />newline
