<!--l. 244--><p class="noindent" >From the snippet of HTML above you can clearly parse other URL embedded in the webpage
http://www.cs.dartmouth.edu/&#x00A0;campbell/index.html The following URLs are embedded:
<!--l. 247--><p class="noindent" ><span class="obeylines-h"><span class="verb"><span 
class="cmtt-10">href="http://www.cs.dartmouth.edu/"</span></span></span> <br 
class="newline" /><span class="obeylines-h"><span class="verb"><span 
class="cmtt-10">href="http://sensorlab.cs.dartmouth.edu"</span></span></span> <br 
class="newline" /><span class="obeylines-h"><span class="verb"><span 
class="cmtt-10">href="http://www.ists.dartmouth.edu"</span></span></span> <br 
class="newline" /><span class="obeylines-h"><span class="verb"><span 
class="cmtt-10">href="http://metrosense.cs.dartmouth.edu/"</span></span></span> <br 
class="newline" /><span class="obeylines-h"><span class="verb"><span 
class="cmtt-10">href="http://metrosense.cs.dartmouth.edu/"</span></span></span> <br 
class="newline" />
<!--l. 253--><p class="noindent" >So this little snippet of HTML tells us that <span 
class="cmbx-10">duplicate links exist</span>. If wanted to imagine that the snippet
represented the complete HTML for the webpage then we could parse that there are 5 embedded URLs in
http://www.cs.dartmouth.edu/&#x00A0;campbell/index.html and that one of them is a duplicate. <span 
class="cmbx-10">TinySearch</span>
<span 
class="cmbx-10">will have to be able to detect and ignore duplicates</span>. More on this when we discuss the design
of the crawler. We will use <span 
class="cmbx-10">hash function and hash table </span>to make sure we only crawler
unique webpages and we will not have to implement a sort function to do this. This is really
cool.
<!--l. 255--><p class="noindent" >When we design the crawler it will rely on <span 
class="cmbx-10">wget </span>to relieve webpages. We have already written a bash shell
script that uses wget in Lab2. We will call wget using the &#8220;system()&#8221; sys call that we used in Lab3. Recall
that you pas wget a URL.
<!--l. 257--><p class="noindent" >Try using wget to download my hompage and store it in a file 1.html (like the crawler does) and then
count the number of URLs on my homepage. There are quite a lot of embedded URLs in my
homepage.
<div 
class="colorbox" id="colorbox4"><div class="BVerbatimInput"><br /><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">NAME</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;wget</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;-</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;GNU</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;Wget</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;Manual</span><br /><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">SYNOPSIS</span><br /><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
class="cmtt-10">&#x00A0;</span><span 
